ssRNA-seq analysis

Project details

Calculate normalized count from ssRNA-seq experiment.

There are 4 columns of single cell data. Column 3 and 4 seems to be the same cell, may need to ask Olga. Column 5 is the pooled cells.

Setup

Load Libraries

#library(tximport)           
library(readr)
library(DESeq2)
library(ggplot2)
library(pheatmap)
library(annotables)
library(RColorBrewer)
#library(grid)
#library(gridExtra)
library(knitr)

Load Data

Load raw count data from directory NGS 2017/Olga RNA-seq/olga.csv.

Create meta table

Create meta file for the experiment.

condition
sNPFR_single1 sNPFR_single1
sNPFR_single2 sNPFR_single2
sNPFR_single3 sNPFR_single3
sNPFR_pooled sNPFR_pooled
5HT_pooled 5HT_pooled

Run DESeq2

Run DESeq2 on matrix data. Require library DESeq2, 2 inputs: tximport result and meata data table.

## Create a DESeqDataSet object
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(df1, sampleTable, ~ condition)

## Run DESeq2
dds <- DESeq(dds)

Quality Control

### Examine size factors
sizeFactors(dds)
## sNPFR_single1 sNPFR_single2 sNPFR_single3  sNPFR_pooled    5HT_pooled 
##    6.03646837    0.16644581    0.03673058   18.08035297    2.56265604
colSums(counts(dds))
## sNPFR_single1 sNPFR_single2 sNPFR_single3  sNPFR_pooled    5HT_pooled 
##      63165070      17191936       1377407      52893614       6494750
### Transform normalized counts to improve the distance for PCA
rld <- rlog(dds, blind=TRUE)
## Warning in sparseTest(counts(object, normalized = TRUE), 0.9, 100, 0.1): the rlog assumes that data is close to a negative binomial distribution, an assumption
## which is sometimes not compatible with datasets where many genes have many zero counts
## despite a few very large counts.
## In this data, for 35.3% of genes with a sum of normalized counts above 100, it was the case 
## that a single sample's normalized count made up more than 90% of the sum over all samples.
## the threshold for this warning is 10% of genes. See plotSparsity(dds) for a visualization of this.
## We recommend instead using the varianceStabilizingTransformation or shifted log (see vignette).
### Plot PCA 
plotPCA(rld, intgroup="condition")

It looks like there are three groups, pool-expected; ss12 & ss7-great; ss10-with distance quite far from ss12&7.

Use heat map to see correlation between samples

rld_mat <- assay(rld)
rld_cor <- cor(rld_mat)
pheatmap(rld_cor)

Calculate normalized counts

normcounts <- counts(dds, normalized=TRUE)

# genes of interest 
# 5 GABA receptors - GRD-LCCH3, Rdl, GABA-B-R1, GABA-B-R2, GABA-B-R3
# 4 Dop receptors - Dop1R1, Dop1R2, Dop2R, DopEcR
# 5 5HT receptor - 5HT1A, 5HT1B, 5HT2A, 5HT2B, 5HT7
gList <- c("Cha","Ace","qvr","hig","VAChT","gfA","nAcRbeta-64B",
           "sNPF","sNPF-R",
           "Ddc","Trh","ple","Gad1","Tdc2","VGAT","VGlut","Vmat",
           "Rdl","GABA-B-R1","GABA-B-R2","GABA-B-R3","Lcch3",
           "5-HT1A","5-HT1B","5-HT2","CG42796","5-HT7",
           "DopEcR","DopR","DopR2","D2R",
           "Oamb","CG18208","Octbeta2R","Octbeta3R","TyrR")

# remove sample 2 since it is outlier from PCA analysis
df2 <- normcounts[match(gList, rownames(normcounts)),c(4,5)]
colnames(df2)[1] <- "sNPFR_single"


## plot normalized count of each genes
library(reshape)
## 
## Attaching package: 'reshape'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:S4Vectors':
## 
##     expand, rename
mdf2 <- melt(df2+1)
colnames(mdf2) <- c("gene","sample","counts")
ggplot(mdf2) + geom_point( aes(x=factor(gene, levels = gList ), y=counts, color=sample), size=3 ) + scale_color_manual(breaks=c("5HT_pooled","sNPFR_pooled"), values=c("red","#028A0F")) + scale_y_log10() +  xlab("Gene") + ylab("Normalized counts") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, face="bold"))
